english:
  title: The Dragon Hall of the Yi River
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The dragon embodies the yang, its virtue aligned with heaven's creative force.
    Submerged, it dwells in the abyss; in flight, it commands the sky.
    The dragon's mystical nature is inscribed in the Book of Changes,
    Yet where does it truly make its dwelling place?

    The Yi River swells and overflows, cascading into ten thousand gorges,
    Two waters converge and flow—their depths remain unknowable.
    Raft-bound men extend their ropes of vine to peer within,
    Seeing only faint shadows of great stones like earthen rooftiles.

    Covered by crystalline waves of tranquility,
    Who could know what lies beneath—
    Grand walls and gates, gardens, birds, and beasts,
    As abundant as any terrestrial realm?

    Palaces of coral, courtyards of jade,
    Where River Lord and water tribes gather to pay homage,
    And the Dragon King's sword and belt chime with jade and silk.
    Though adorned with imperial robes and crimson slippers,
    No trace of the sea's salt clings to them.

    On the riverbank stands a sacred shrine, dignified and tall,
    Its shadow entering the waters—mere fancy and imagination.
    Our king descends with fragrant offerings in spring and autumn,
    The temple grounds solemn, pristine, and well-maintained.
    Rain and sunshine come in their proper season,
    Grain fills the fields, and people live free from illness,
    Old and young alike at leisure and at play.

    The dragon responds with benevolence, bestowing a hundred blessings,
    Not merely upon this one region of the Yi River,
    But far and wide. I have composed this poem,
    And surely the dragon will hear it.
    The dragon will smile at me, for I have bridged the hidden and the manifest.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Yi River (伊川) is referenced as a significant waterway with spiritual significance in this region.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Book of Changes' (周易) refers to the I Ching, where the dragon appears as a symbol of cosmic power and transformation.
  - key: ''
    value: River Lord (馮夷) is a traditional Chinese deity associated with rivers and water.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of coral palaces and jade courtyards reflects traditional Chinese paradises and celestial realms.
